## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAARUlEQVQ4jWN0cHD4z4ADHDhwgHHOvPk45RkYGBgYcBmAz2BkwEJIASEXEDQgJSmRcQi4AF+AEYwFSgHheKY1GHXBYHABANEoImfx0KvuAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Block
The most important *block-level *element is *Block*. Basically a *Block *is nothing else but a paragraph. Technically spoken it is a container for *inline-level *elements. From the perspective of the user, a block may be considered as a paragraph.

Usually a block is used to generate a text passage. To generate text content, the text elements do not have to be created manually. A block is simply created (or an existing selected) and the text is entered. If the block is empty, the *Doxee Template Designer *automatically creates a new text element.

Also the keyboard can be used to create a new block just after the existing one, by pressing ENTER within the block.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAQklEQVQ4jWNgGGjAiMyxt7fvYGRkLCegp+LAgQOdMA4TVV2ADGxsbARZWFjeMTAwvD9w4IAQLnUUu2DUgFEDBgcAALurChffPMupAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Text
*Text *elements are the most important static elements in *Doxee Template Designer*. Every static (i.e. manually entered) text is represented by a text element. *Text *elements may contain single characters or entire paragraphs. Text that does not fit into a single line will automatically be split across multiple lines.

Like all inline-elements, *Text *elements must be placed inside *Blocks*. While typing in the *Desiger View*, *Text *elements are automatically placed within *Blocks*.

The easiest way to change *Text Styles *is to set the relevant properties to the containing *Block*. It is possible, however, to set them directly on *Text *elements, for example to emphasize single words. The most efficient way to maintain layout for bigger documents is to use *Styles *(see chapter [Styles](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-styles)).

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Image
Including graphics in a template is easy using the *Image *element. *Images *are inline elements, so they can be put on a line of text. However, it is no problem to make an *Image *stand by itself by simply putting the *Image *in a *Block *of its own.

If no source file is assigned, or in case the given URL just cannot be resolved (e.g. because an XPath expression is used), to an *Image *element, a *placeholder icon *is displayed. The easiest way to assign a source file to an *Image *element is to double click the placeholder and choosing an image in the file browser.

*Doxee Template Designer *supports a wide range of image formats. In the *Designer View *the common standard formats (e.g. *JPG*, *GIF *and *PNG*) can be displayed. However, a rendered document can also contain other formats, like *PDF*. Formats that cannot be displayed by the editor will cause the image to show up as the placeholder icon in the *Designer *tab. The list of supported file formats depends on the selected PDF renderer. Formats supported by the included FOP rendering engine are:

- GIF

- BMP

- EPS (only when generating PostScript)

- JPEG

- PNG

- SVG (with limitations)

- TIFF (with limitations)

- EMF (only when generating RTF)

For further details, please consult the [**Apache FOP documentation**](https://xmlgraphics.apache.org/fop/trunk/graphics.html).

### Important Image Properties
The following properties apply specifically to *Image *elements:

**Attribute**

**Description**

*content-width / content-height (Advanced &gt; Area Dimension &gt;)*

These two properties specify the *width *and *height *of the *Image*. If they are set to auto, the image’s default size will be used. scale-to- fit will scale the image to fit the dimensions specified by *block-progression-dimension *and *inline-progression-dimension *(which should in this case be set to specific values instead of the default auto). You may also manually specify an arbitrary size.

*Scaling (Advanced &gt; Area Dimension &gt;)*

When the *content-width *and *content-height *properties are used, this property controls how the image is scaled. The default value uniform will modify the horizontal and vertical scaling factors so that the image’s original aspect ratio is retained. To force a custom width and height even if it changes the aspect ratio, set this property to non- uniform.

*Src (Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt;)*

Specifies the location of the *Image *file. This property does not have to be set manually. Instead it is possible to choose *Select image *in the context menu to open a dialog which allows selecting the source file. The *Image *element can be used as a "semi-dynamic" element by specifying the source file by an XPath expression. This allows using a different source file for the same *Image *element depending on a document’s dynamic input.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAIAAACQkWg2AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAPElEQVQoke2OwREAEBDElhZRSXo8uloVMO4vr7wyKYAyVEmtj9bHo9RUXlLJLgmIuWIuwLbtu/ylv3RgA68MpKHw6K5vAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Table
A *Table *is a set of *cells*, arranged vertically into *columns *and horizontally into *rows*. Each *cell *is a separate container for block-level elements.

### ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAIAAACQkWg2AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAPklEQVQoke2OMREAIAzEHsxgDAcxgLqCq0cBHN3JlCmXAihDldT6aH08Sk3lJZXskoCYK+YCbNu+y1/6Swc2TBOlN+SAUlAAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) Table Header
The *Table *Header is an element that is located above the table. Especially for complex structures, which uses the repeat at the lines (see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Dynamic Value](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#dynamic-value)); it is recommended to dispose the table header separately. It is also convenient to use headers to specify different properties.

> Note

It is not necessary to use table header and footer. Tables with only one table body element work as well.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 86. Elements &gt; Table*

### ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAIAAACQkWg2AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAM0lEQVQokWMsLi5mIAUwMTAwBIeEBoeEEslgIsl4BgYGRoqcpJ7SoJ7SgJ8x6qRRJ+EAAM2VO0mwgdMRAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Table Body
*Table Body *is the main element for the content of a table. There is no limitation for its size. It consists of an arbitrary number of rows. *Table Rows *contain *Table Cells*, which can be filled with any *block-level *element. Most commonly a *Block *containing whatever *inline-level *element will be the content of a *Table Cell*.

In order to enter text to a table cell it is not necessary to manually insert a *Block*, but just to start typing in the desired *Cell *and the *Block *will be inserted automatically.

### ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAIAAACQkWg2AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAATklEQVQoke3OMQ0AIRBE0c+aQRDgAAdjAHWAqz0HhC0uueKm+tXkJUlEZkCprdR2GRa6B1KUhKS59lxbkru7+zl+0jdIBuQ+ch+X8T7pATbnimnlWDcDAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Table Footer
The *Table Footer *is an element that is located below the table. Especially for complex structures, which uses the repeat element at table lines (see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Dynamic Value](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#dynamic-value)); it is recommended to conduct the table footer separately. It is also convenient to use a footer to set different properties. The table header is used more commonly than the table footer element (see section ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAIAAACQkWg2AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAPklEQVQoke2OMREAIAzEHsxgDAcxgLqCq0cBHN3JlCmXAihDldT6aH08Sk3lJZXskoCYK+YCbNu+y1/6Swc2TBOlN+SAUlAAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) [Table Header](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#table-header)) though.

### Manipulating tables and their elements
It is well worth pointing out how to manipulate *Tables *and their elements in a separate chapter.

In general the most common functions are available in the context menu opened by right clicking an element either in the *Outline View *or in the *Designer *tab of the *Main View*.

By manipulating the following actions are meant:

- adding rows

- adding columns

- merging cells

horizontally

- vertically

- splitting cells

horizontally

- vertically

- deleting rows

- deleting columns

Applying to the matching element the figures below show the possible actions.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 87. Elements &gt; Table: Insert column*

When inserting a new *Table Column *this way by choosing *Insert *in the *Table Columns *node all new cell elements are automatically added to the *Table Rows*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 88. Elements &gt; Table: Delete column*

When deleting a *Table Column *this way all cells within this column and their content are deleted as well.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 89. Elements &gt; Table: Delete row*

The function *Delete Row *deletes the currently selected row including all cells and their content.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 90. Elements &gt; Table: Delete row/column containing the selected cell*

Deleting a *Table Cell *itself makes not much sense, as a *Table Row *must contain either the same number of cells as columns have been defined or reach this number including the *column-spans *set by merging cells.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 91. Elements &gt; Table: Insert row before/after selected row*

When inserting a *Table Row *this way a new row, filled with the number of cells as columns have been defined for this table, is inserted.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 92. Elements &gt; Table: Insert row/column before/after selected cell*

Inserting a *Table Cell *itself into a row makes no sense, as a row needs to contain either the same number of cells as columns have been defined or reach this number including the column-spans set by merging cells. Therefore it is possible to either add columns or rows, but not cells directly. (It is still possible to copy/paste cells, in order to create more complex layouts using *Conditions*, etc.)

Choosing *Insert Row after *inserts one row with the number of cells as columns have been defined for the table. Choosing *Insert column *inserts one column to the table and adds the “new cell” to all rows.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 93. Elements &gt; Table: Merge cell with left/right/below cell*

**Attribute**

**Description**

*number-columns-spanned (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Table &gt;) or number-rows-spanned (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Table &gt;)*

Using *Merge with *cells are merged. It is possible to set *horizontal *and *vertical column- span*. The *column-span *can however also be adjusted “manually” using *Properties *&gt; *Advanced &gt; Table &gt; number-columns- spanned *(and *Advanced &gt; Table &gt; number- rows-spanned *for rows). By changing the *column-span *this way it is important to keep an eye on the consistency of the number of columns defined for the table, the sum of the *column-span *and the actual number of cells.

Having merged cells the option *Split cell *allows splitting the merged cell again.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 94. Elements &gt; Table: Split merged cells*

### Table trouble shooting &amp; table properties
**Attribute**

**Description**

*number-columns-spanned (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Table &gt;) or number-rows-spanned (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Table &gt;)*

set the column-span manually

As a consequence of different ways to correctly merge cells the most likely errors to happen might be inconsistencies between the number of columns defined for one table and the actual number of cells in a row. *Doxee Template Designer *does not hinder users from deleting cells manually, but a “clean” design and programming is nevertheless necessary in order to create templates that can be rendered. Therefore if a cell shall be deleted, it is important to consider if cells should be merged instead. Hence too many or too few cells in a row are the most common error source.

Another possible error is an empty row (which, however, also equals too few cells in a row) or cells copied into a *Repeat *or *Condition *without being contained in a row.

Usually the *Problems View *(see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Problems](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-views-1#problems)) and a warning overlay icon should inform about possible problems.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAIElEQVQ4jWNgGAXDBTg4OPx3cHD4Tw6fib5OHQWDFAAAJqoN+43FU1oAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) Leader
*Leaders *are used to fill horizontal space between two inline elements. The width of this space can either be specified manually, or set to use the *maximum width *available on the element’s line. The second option is the default and typically applied when using *Leaders *to separate chapter titles and page numbers in a Table of Contents, for instance. The space taken by the *Leader *can either be blank or filled with dots or a continuous line.

### Important Leader properties
The following properties apply specifically to leaders:

**Attribute**

**Description**

*leader-length*

Specifies the “width” of the space created by the *Leader*. It is possible to either manually enter a measurement or to use the predefined value auto, which is also the default. auto will make the *Leader *fill up as much space as the current alignment dictates. For most alignments this results in a small horizontal space; however the justify alignment will set the width of auto *Leaders *so that they fill as much of the line as possible.

The last line of a justified paragraph normally uses left alignment, but an auto *Leader’s *width depends on the alignment of the line in which it occurs. Therefore, if your leader is placed in the last line of its paragraph, be sure to set the paragraph’s text-align-last property to justify. Otherwise, the leader will only use a minimal horizontal space.

*Leader pattern*

Specifies the look of the leader. *space: *leaves the leader space blank *dots: *uses dots

*rule: *uses a continuous line to fill the space generated by the leader

*use-content: *uses the content of the leader element. Drag and drop elements into the leader element to define its content.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAASklEQVQ4jWNgoBAwMjAwMDg4OPxHFjxw4AAjsQYwwRj79+9n2L9/P8kuYCKsBD9ggTEcHR1RJNC9hQM4UOqA0UAcDUQGBobBEIgA65kh0AOPstsAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) List
A List is a container for block-level elements which are marked with bullets, dashes, numbers or other user specified characters.

Every block inside the list element will get its own list mark. This makes the creation of simple text lists very easy. By typing text into a new list, a list item (block element) is added and pressing ENTER, creates a new block and therefore a new list item.

### List properties
**Attribute**

**Description**

*list-start-value (Advanced &gt; Bullets And Numbering &gt;)*

For numbered lists this determines the number of the first entry in the list. If no value (other than 1) is entered to the property, this is "1". Every additional list entry will get the number of its predecessor plus 1.

**Attribute**

**Description**

*list-style-type (Advanced &gt; Bullets And Numbering &gt;)*

Determines the type of list marks to be used for the list. The following options are available:

circle, dash, decimal, decimal-leading-zero, disc, lower roman, upper roman, lower alpha, upper alpha

*list-value-prefix (Advanced &gt; Bullets And Numbering &gt;)*

For a numbered list, this defines the text that is printed before the current number. In nested lists, you can use the *%inherit *directive to include the next-higher list label.

*list-value-suffix (Advanced &gt; Bullets And Numbering &gt;)*

For a numbered list, this defines the text that is printed after the current number. You can still use the *%inherit *directive here, but it is typically used only in the prefix.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAwAAAALCAIAAADEEvsIAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAASklEQVQYlY2QwQ3AMAgDXdTBYHKP5j6SoKgKpf4hHXAytOLuKmIAAEQE6tggSDbQNzGhNvdrPspdkn5dyu1SLuvpe2rekdxlj+IPa8tRnBffxR4AAAAASUVORK5CYII=) Numbering
Starting with version 6.2, numbering schemas can be defined in Template Designer. Numbering schemas are used for automated numbering of e.g. chapters, images, or tables. For easier use, four pre-defined numbering schemes are provided in each new template: chapter, figure, table, appendix These schemas can be edited or copied and applied to block elements.

There is no limit on the number of schemes, either defined locally or imported from a referenced resource. Local schemas can be renamed or deleted.

The easiest way to set the properties for the numbering schemes (and also for numebred blocks) if the property sheet *Numbering*.

The following properties apply to the numbering schemes:

**Property**

**Description**

Name

Unique name that identifies the schema within the template

Value

(Start-)Value for the numbering

Pattern

decimal (1,2,3…), decimal-leading-zero (01,02,03…), lower-alpha (a,b,c…), upper- alpha (A,B,C), lower-roman (i,ii,iii…), upper- roman (I,II,III…)

Prefix

A text that is displayed before the generated number (e.g. "Chapter "); Spaces can be used.

Suffix

A text that is displayed after the generated number (e.g. a bracket ")")

Separator

A text that is displayed between two numbering levels (e.g. "." so decimal results in 1.2 or 1.2.3 instead of just 12 or 123)

Margin left

Distance between the laft page border and the numbering (e.g. 10mm)

Margin right

Distance between the numbering and the following text (e.g. 5mm)

**Property**

**Description**

Width

Total width of the numbering (e.g. 50mm). Note that the total of the margins left and right should not exceed the width.)

After defining a scheme it can be applied to a block element. Select the block in question and enter the name of the desired numbering scheme in the property sheet *Numbering*. For referenceing the numbered element it needs a unique ID. The property *level *selects the depth of the current numbering. Level 1: 1; Level 2: 1.2; Level 3: 1.2.3; The default level is 1.

### Numbering Reference
The palette element *Numbering Reference *makes a reference to a numbered block (e.g. to a certain chapter) from within the template.

Place the element at the desired location and set the properties in the property sheet *Numbering*. The property *Reference ID *identifies the target of the reference. Further you can choose whether the referenced number, text, and/or page number should be displayed for the reference and whether the reference should be rendered as a link so that the reader can jump to the referenced location. As long as the ID is not changed, the reference will adapt automatically when the template changes.

### Table of Contents
The palette element *Table of Contents *creates a listing of all the numbered elements of a given scheme. Place the element at the desired location and enter the name of the scheme in the property sheet *Numbering*. At design time you will see a placeholder for the table of contents. It will be generated during the XSL transformation.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAATUlEQVQ4jc1SQQoAMAiysYf59H7W7q0gaLA8WolZwG9IRJK0iFfVq391HQwQyPatgKS1HeyIjNLO8M6Bz8K7yOoDztgVSP++OisdAQA4hJ8XGSMcbfoAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) Container
A (block-level) *Container *works simply as a container in which other block-level elements can be put. The purpose is to have a central element for specifying properties on a set of blocks, as the child elements of the container will inherit the container’s properties.

Another common purpose for containers is specifying borders around multiple elements. Specifying the same border properties on two subsequent blocks would result in two subsequent rectangular bordered blocks. To have one single border around both blocks, put both blocks into a container and specify the border settings on the container.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Instream Foreign Object
The *Instream Foreign Object *element is a highly advanced element. It can be used to output parser specific extensions or to output dynamically created *SVG*-code.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAN0lEQVQ4je3MoQ3AMBADwEsn8+jeLCUB4SUFb2JZsm4l2W1Xkg1tF5wd9Gr3Fx4fM8AAA/wFeAGjNg/flvjZEAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==) Barcode
*Barcodes *are easy to use in *Doxee Template Designer*. By dragging a *Barcode *element to the position in the template it shall be displayed at, a placeholder icon is placed.

**Attribute**

**Description**

*Type*

To every barcode element a type has to be assigned, otherwise it cannot be generated. Currently a wide range of about 38 barcode types is supported (e.g. QR-code, Datamatrix, and EAN).

*Expression*

The value the rendered *Barcode *shall hold, is entered by double clicking the place holder symbol. *Barcodes *most likely will contain dynamic content. If the expression is a static text or value, it must be surrounded by quotes. Note: For the Swiss-QR barcode type, the *expression *property is not used. The data should be filled into a whole array of type- specific fields instead.

*Display text*

By selecting this option, the barcode text is displayed below the barcode.

> Important

Changes are only shown in the PDF preview!

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Chart
A *Chart *element is a placeholder for a graphic element that is used during the XSL transformation. It is generated dynamically and it is a virtual representation of data. Since version 5.3 the following diagram types are supported: Bar, Pie, Line, Scatter Plot, Spider Chart.

You can find examples of pie and bar charts in the installation in the directory *Template Designer/Examples/en/Advanced/Diagrams*.

Standard attributes of the *Chart *element:

##### chart-definition
Each diagram element needs an XML structure, which defines the type and representation of the chart. It is best practice to define a separate *Data Input *element to map the *chart-definition *XML into the template.

The integrated XML editor supports schema checking for XMLs. Activate them by adding the following attributes to the main node of your XML:

`xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="infinica://resources/xsd/infinica-jfreechart.xsd"`A detailed example with all options can be found in the Template Designer installation directory under: ..\Documentation\xsd\infinica-jfreechart.xsd

When you open the XML file in Template Designer, typing &lt; will show an entry helper with all the elements that are valid at the current position:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

*Figure 95. Entry helper for the chart definition*

Example of the definition:

`&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;pie legend="true" width="400" height="320" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema
instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="infinica://resources/xsd/infinica-jfreechart.xsd"&gt;
    &lt;title width="250"&gt;
        &lt;position&gt;top&lt;/position&gt;
        &lt;text&gt;Pie Chart - Demo 2&lt;/text&gt;
        &lt;font name="Courier New" size="15" bold="false" italic="false"/&gt;
        &lt;textAlignment&gt;justify&lt;/textAlignment&gt;
        &lt;fgColor red="0" green="0" blue="255"/&gt;
        &lt;padding top="20" bottom="10" left="0" right="0"/&gt;
    &lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;plot circular="true" sectionDepth="0.5"&gt; &lt;!-- sectionDepth sets the diameter of the ring
--&gt;
      &lt;outline&gt;
      &lt;/outline&gt;
      &lt;centerText text="Center" /&gt;
      &lt;sections&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt; &lt;!-- margin btwn the rings --&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt;
          &lt;section explodePercent="0.03" /&gt;
      &lt;/sections&gt;
      &lt;label visible = 'false'&gt;
           &lt;links visible ="true"/&gt;

    &lt;/plot&gt;

&lt;/pie&gt;`##### chart-data
Pass the data for your chart into this attribute. The *data *section within the *chart- definition *XML defines how the values from *chart-data *are used.

Example data input for a pie chart:

`&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;chart&gt;
    &lt;pie&gt;
        &lt;entry name="One" value="35.94" /&gt;
        &lt;entry name="Two" value="7.94" /&gt;
        &lt;entry name="Three" value="25.77" /&gt;
        &lt;entry name="Four" value="11.69" /&gt;
        &lt;entry name="Five" value="6.51" /&gt;
        &lt;entry name="Six" value="12.15" /&gt;
    &lt;/pie&gt;
&lt;/chart&gt;
`The above XML creates the following chart diagram:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 96. Pie Chart Diagram*

To manually adjust the color of the diagram, the node color can be used as the outline in the &lt;sections&gt; element. This feature only works from 5.4.5.1. on. The following is an example with manual coloring of a section:

`&lt;section&gt;
    &lt;outline&gt;
        &lt;color blue="255" green="255" red="255"/&gt;
        &lt;basicStroke width="3" /&gt;
    &lt;/outline&gt;
    &lt;color blue="10" green="112" red="100"/&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;`##### chart-image-format
By default, charts are generated as vector graphics (*svg *format). This produces the best result for most use cases, both in terms of image quality and memory consumption. If the results are not satisfactory for your particular combination of renderer and output format, you may want to test some other image formats, e.g. *png *or *tif*. For more information, see the examples from the infinica-jfreechart.xsd file in the Documentation folder.

> Important

Changes are only shown in the PDF preview!

> Important

The most common error is not having simultaneously proper chart-data AND chart-definition set, otherwise rendering will fail! (please see the screenshot for your reference below, by double clicking on the chart these options have to be set accordingly)

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAwAAAAQCAYAAAAiYZ4HAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAZElEQVQokWN0cHD4z0ACYGFgYGDYv38/UYodHR0hGmAcfABmKAu6ACHASKofGGZOm/afWDBz2rT/cCfNmj4dbkhaZiYKHyaG4geYAC4+DGC1AZtNBG3AJc6EVRUeQHKwDoekAQAatlXlX22E7QAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==) Static Page Content
*Static Page Content *is used to fill regions of a document with a constant, i.e. static content. The most common use case is to generate *headers *and *footers *for a template. XSL-FO (and so does *Doxee Template Designer*) offers four regions for static content:

- top

- bottom

- left

- right

The image below shows the assignable areas of a page. The size of the regions is adjusted using the *Page Master *dialog (see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Page Masters](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-document-structure#page-masters)). By selecting the options *Precedence &gt; Top *and/or *Precedence &gt; Bottom *in the *Page Masters *dialog it is possible to define if the left and right region starts on top of the document or below the top region. The same applies to the bottom precedence.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In order to create a new *Static Page Content *element simply right-click the *Page Sequence*

node (see Chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Template Parts](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-document-structure#template-parts)) in the *Outline View *and choose *Add new Static Page Content*. A popup opens to choose which kind of *Static Page Content *shall be added. A *Static Page Content *element, containing a *Block *element is added for the chosen area. Alternatively it is possible to drag a *Static Page Content *element from the *Palette *to the *Page Sequence *node in the *Outline View*. The further proceeding is the same.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAsAAAAICAIAAACgWpLfAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAaUlEQVQYlX2Ouw3AIAxELyid12AYBmEAOlaAjnEYhjGOmhRWFOejvOrkd5JvI5lSGmPgTggh5wzAiUhrzXv/qQE4AI+S1QCwTkjGGEspy0DS4RcR2TXNOXWvTrZfnNV66r3XWq/GQ79LB+kdT1Flu1PAAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Marker
Markers are used to display actual dynamic values in a static content (headers or footers). A classic example is the transfer of a sum to the next page.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 98. transfer of a sum*

### Differences between Marker and Variable
A normal variable cannot be used to display carryovers of sums, because it is already resolved in the transformation step, when it is not yet known where a page break occurs.

However, the marker is retained as a dynamic element at first and will only be resolved when rendering. Thus, the current value of the sum is only taken at the end (or start) of the page during rendering (of a PDF for example).

### Utilisation
#### ![](data:image/png;base64,) Set Marker
![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 99. set marker*

In the present example, a sum of ascending numbers is composed. The variable *sum *contains the sum total, whereas *sum_prev *contains the value of the transfer (carry over). This variable is used for the marker.

*Set marker *shows you a mark to a name and any content. If this content includes variables, the current values are transferred to the label at rendering time.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 100. sum_prev*

As you can see in the example above, a marker can contain static (e.g. text), as well as dynamic elements. The marker *sum_prev *must be initialized (empty) first, so that no transfer is displayed on the first page.

#### ![](data:image/png;base64,) Show Marker
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

*Figure 101. show marker*

*Show marker *can now display the current marker content by specifying the name of the marker in the property *retrieve-class-name *in e.g. a header or a footer.

**Attribute**

**Description**

*retrieve-boundary*

With this attribute, the range is set, in which the current marker can be gathered.

*retrieve-position*

This attribute is used to decide which value has to be taken.

*first-starting-within-page*

This attribute gives the first value after the page break (as it has been set in the present example of the sum transfer in the header).

*last-ending-within-page*

With this attribute, the last value on the page is used (as in the present example of the total sum in the footer chosen). Thus, the total sum will appear only once on the last page.

For a detailed explanation of the various options, please see the W3C XSL reference (via the WWW-button ![](data:image/png;base64,)).

### Text Field as Composer date-picker
The *Text Field *element can be customized to allow the *Doxee Composer *user to enter a date through text input or choose (pick) the desired date from the pop-up/interactive calendar.

*Composer date-picker &gt; Text Field*

*![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*

To support a date input, configure the *content-type *attribute of the *Text Field *element via *Advanced &gt; Property &gt; Miscellaneous *by setting the value as *date*. When the *content_type *is set without any formatting pattern, calendar date formatting will be performed according to the system’s environment. The most common date pattern *DDMMYYYY *can be set to the property *Miscellaneous &gt; content-type *as ***date:DD.MM.YYYY***. The *format pattern *for the *content-type *must be in the syntax permitted by [*moment.js*](https://momentjs.com/docs/)*  *library.

*Composer date-picker &gt; content-type*

*![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*

The date-picker can also adapt custom formats defined by the user. There are a wide range of options that can be used to format different components of the date (day, month, year). For instance, you can display date as default value by setting the date and its format via *Advanced &gt; Property &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; Form Field &gt; formfield-text*. The attribute *formfield- text *can also be defined using an XPath expression. For example, you can format and display the current date as the default calendar value in the date input field.

*Composer date-picker &gt; formfield-text*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Content Flipper
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

*Figure 106. Content Flipper*

Content Flipper is a *Composer *element that inserts a carousel-style slideshow into the

*Composer *preview. It can also be used to create an expandable/collapsible area in *Composer*.

The final selection of elements which will be displayed in a rendered document is made in

*Composer*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

##### Structure of a complete Content Flipper element:
- Content Flipper: A container.

Content Flipper Branch: A single element. One Content Flipper may contain one or more Content Flipper Branches, which may be wrapped in conditions and loops.

Header: Contains inline text. May or may not be displayed in Composer.

- Body: Contains elements. This is the actual interactive or collapsible content of the element.

### Grouping of Radio-buttons
Given that a Radio-button normally always should have at least a second Radio-button as the opponent, the membership of the various Radio-buttons must be specified through their names. This means, that multiple Radio-buttons are supposed to have the same name but different values. When a Radio-button is selected, the value of the respective button is transmitted.

### Use custom SVG-icons for radio buttons and checkboxes in PDF (intermediate)
From version 6.1 SP1 on you can use custom SVG-icons for PDF (target = intermediate) instead of the standard icons coming with the product. There are four icons you can replace by using a custom SVG-resource path:

- Checkbox unchecked: checkboxUnchecked.svg

- Checkbox checked: checkboxChecked.svg

- Radiobutton unchecked: radioUnchecked.svg

- Radiobutton checked: radioChecked.svg

You can edit the path to the SVG-icons in the preferences of Template Designer under *XSL- FO *in the field *Infinica SVG Resources*. The path has to end with a slash "/".

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Script
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 113. script*

The processing of form elements by PDF readers happens via scripts which are written in JavaScript. First, the action type "script" has to be selected. Then the code itself has to be inserted into the Details field.

### Area of validity
#### Global scripts
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 114. global scripts*

Scripts which are stored in the *Outline View *under *Scripts *contain general, global functions (you can e.g. define script functions for rounding or input checks) and variables, which can be used directly in the elements.

Unfortunately, it is not possible to directly reference to an external JS-file. *Template Parts *can be used to work around this problem, so that these general functions are stored centrally and don’t have to be maintained redundantly.

#### Scripts for graphic elements
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 115. scripts for graphic elements*

The scripts, which are stored below graphical elements, are always linked to an event. Please use a different script for each event.

### Script attributes
#### Action type
**Action type**

**Description**

*hide*

Hides the form elements listed in the *details*

field or all fields if left empty

*reset*

Form is reset

*script*

Individual coding in JavaScript

*show*

Shows the form elements listed in the *details*

field or all fields if left empty

*submit*

Form is submitted

**Options**

This option is used to declare additional properties (e.g. which type of data) for *submit *and

*reset*. Most commonly used Options are listed and described below.

**Option**

**Description**

Excludes the Form elements listed in the

_details_field from the reset action

#### Target
The address for the web service that processes the data on submit is entered in the Target field.

#### Events / Trigger
The link between scripts and fields takes place via Events. If e.g. a mouse button in a field is pressed or the field is exited, the system triggers an event that is encrypted using the *Trigger*.

The following table shows all available Events and their *Triggers*. The list is sorted in the order which event occurs first and is processed by the system:

**Trigger**

**Event**

**Description**

E

Mouse Enter

Mouse pointer moves into the field

X

Mouse Exit

Mouse pointer leaves the field

D

Mouse Down

Mouse button is pressed on the field

F

Focus

Field receives focus

U

Mouse Up

Mouse button is released on the field

K

Keystroke

A key is pressed in the field

K

SelectionChange

Selection has changed (only for the listbox and combobox)

V

Validate

Entry is complete - field can be checked

B

Blur

Field loses focus

#### Example Validate
The JavaScript code can be accessed directly on the event information event. The following examples show various input validations, which are anchored at the Validate event (*Trigger *= V). An acoustic signal is generated, a message is displayed and the return code is set to false at each error. The last one prevents the user from exiting the field.

At Validate, the entered value has not yet been transferred in the field and thus it has to be queried through event.value.

Numeric entry (allowed: 0-9, comma and period):

`var value = "" + event.value.replace(/[^,.\d]/g, "");
if (value.length &lt; event.value.length || !isFinite(value)) {
  app.beep(0);
  app.alert("Invalid value in field" + event.target.name);
  event.rc = false; }
`Input between 0 and 100 allowed:

`if (event.value &lt; 0 || event.value &gt; 100) {
  app.beep(0);
  app.alert("Value must be between 0 and 100");
  event.rc = false;
}`### Further information

The following code sample shows all the attributes, their contents and functions which are available to a field (here: Feedback):

`console.show();
console.clear();

var feedback = getField("feedback");
showAttributesAndFunctions(feedback);

function showAttributesAndFunctions(field) {
  if (field != null)
      console.println("Attributes:");
      console.println(".................");
      for (var i in field){
           try {
               if(typeof field[i] != "function") {
                   console.println(i + ": " + field[i]);
               }
           }
           catch(err) { }
      }
      console.println("=================");
      console.println("Functions:");
      console.println(".................");
      for (var i in field){
          try {
              if(typeof field[i] == "function") {
                  console.println(i);
              }
          }
          catch(err){ }
      }
  }
}
`## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Dynamic Value
*Dynamic Value *is probably one of the most important elements in *Doxee Template Designer*. *Dynamic values *represent field references to data in the *data source *assigned to the template. The field reference is an *XPath expression *referring to a node in an XML file.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 118. Elements &gt; Dynamic Value*

See chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Data Inputs](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-views-1#data-inputs) to learn how a *dynamic data source *is added to a template.

> Note

All elements containing dynamic content follow a blue colour scheme. So the icons of these elements, the labels in the *Designer *tab in the *Main *View and the labels in the *Outline View *are blue.

### Formatting Dynamic Content
In its plain form, a Dynamic Value displays the text of the referenced data node. For data nodes that represent numerical or date/time values, some formatting options are available.

- *Number *Specify a pattern and a format (references a  ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Decimal Format](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#decimal-format))

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 119. Formatting a number*

- *Decimal Alignment *is a special case of formatting a number. It ensures that the decimal character (usually a dot or a comma, depending on the referenced Decimal Format) is at a fixed position, which allows for neat lists of numbers even when they have different lengths.

![](data:image/png;base64,) *Figure 120. Decimal alignment*

- *Number as Word *converts the number into words. Supported languages are *en *and *de*.

![](data:image/png;base64,) *Figure 121. Number as Word*

- *date *and/or *time *provides fine control over display of the date/time fields.

![](data:image/png;base64,) *Figure 122. Date/time formatting*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAPElEQVQ4jWM0X3H7PwMOcDJClXHOvPk45RkYGBhY8EkyMDAwpCQlMlJkwKgLCLuAYkAwnmkORl0wGFwAAMCCHlYJsZLyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Dynamic Block
A *dynamic Block *can integrate XML-compliant HTML (e.g. XHTML) into the document. It is important that the HTML file has a BODY definition, since this area is then displayed.

Example:

`&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;data&gt;
    &lt;xhtml&gt;
         &lt;html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"&gt;
             &lt;head&gt;
                 &lt;title&gt;XHTML Sample&lt;/title&gt;
             &lt;/head&gt;
             &lt;body&gt;
                 &lt;p&gt;XHTML Sample with &lt;b&gt;bold&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;i&gt;italic&lt;/i&gt; text.&lt;/p&gt;
             &lt;/body&gt;
         &lt;/html&gt;
    &lt;/xhtml&gt;
&lt;/data&gt;`The result looks like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 123. result - Dynamic Block*

### Utilisation
First, the HTML file is defined as data input:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 124. Data Input*

Therefore, you enter an appropriate name (here „xml1“) and specify among XML file the desired HTML file.

The dynamic block can now be inserted to the desired location by indicating the XPath reference to the data input (here: $xml1/data/xhtml)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 125. insert XPath reference*

> Note

All elements containing dynamic content follow a blue colour scheme. So the icons of these elements, the labels in the *Designer *tab in the *Main *view and the labels in the *Outline *view are blue.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Variable
*Variables *can be used like programming variables. When creating a *Variable *element, a name and an XPath expression must be provided.

*Variables *can either be dragged to a position in the template and i.e. used within a *repeat *to set it dynamically or declared in the *Global Variables *node in the *Outline View *to generate a static *Variable*, which can be accessed within the whole document. Afterwards the *Variable *can be called via *Dynamic Value *elements (see Chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Dynamic Value](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#dynamic-value)) using &lt;$VARIABLE_NAME&gt;.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Page Number
The *Page Number *element allows inserting the *current *or *last *page number to a template. A *Page Number *element may be inserted to any place in the template by dragging a *Page Number *element from the Palette to the desired spot. A placeholder (#) for the page numbers is displayed in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *view.

### Page Number properties
**Attribute**

**Description**

*page-number (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt;)*

Set to *current *(the default value), the *Page Number *element is replaced with the number of the current page in the PDF output. Set to *last*, the element is replaced with the total number of pages.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Link
The *Link *element can be used to create internal and external links. *Link *elements work alike HTML links, therefore the content has to be wrapped with a link. That is, if a *Link *element does not have any content, the link cannot be displayed in the PDF output. *Link *elements must not be confused with, or automatically be considered, as text links. *Link *elements may contain any type of content. For use as hyperlink the text contained by the Link element still needs to be formatted as desired, i.e. the program does not apply any automatic – possibly unwanted – formatting to the text.

### Link properties
**Attribute**

**Description**

*link type (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt;)*

It is possible to make the *Link *either internal or external. Using internal creates links within the template, whereas external can be used to create hyperlinks.

*external-destination (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Dynamic Effects &gt;)*

Defines the target of the link, if set to external

*internal-destination (Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Dynamic Effects &gt;)*

Used to determine the target of an internal link

> Note

Setting the options is also possible via the graphical properties sheet.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Repeat
The *Repeat *element is used to display repeated data structures. For example a customer that holds multiple bank accounts, whose data structure could look like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 126. Example XML file*

Using the *Repeat *element it is possible to set a loop to customer/accounts/account and then

to insert *Dynamic Value *elements (see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Dynamic Value](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#dynamic-value)) for id, balance and limit. If the *Repeat *element is *wrapped around *a table row, the row would be filled with the values of one account iterating through all accounts.

*Repeat *elements are inserted the easiest by right clicking an element in the *Outline View *and then choosing *Wrap with &gt; Repeat*. Having the *XPath *copied from the *Data Inputs view *or entering it manually the *Repeat *is set to the desired value. It is also possible to *unwrap *a *Repeat *the same way it was wrapped. It is also possible to insert a *Repeat *to the template from the *Palette*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 127. Elements &gt; Repeat wrap with*

> Note

All *logical *elements (*Repeat*, *Condition *and *Condition Branch*) follow an orange colour scheme. So the icons of these elements, the labels in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *View and the labels in the *Outline *view are orange.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Condition
*Conditions *are logical constraints defined using XPath and work similar to the *if construct *in several programming languages. Using *Condition *elements it is possible to check the content of data fields, in order to display different content in a template. Using the *XPath Editor *(see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [XPath-Editor](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-views-1#xpatheditor)), it is easily possible to edit complex functions.

Alike *Repeat *elements, *Conditions *are inserted the easiest by right clicking an element in the *Outline View *and then choosing *Wrap with &gt; Condition*. As an element can be *wrapped with *a *Condition*, it can of course be *unwrapped *the same way. It is also possible to insert a *Condition *to the template from the Palette.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 128. Elements &gt; Condition wrap with*

> Note

All *logical *elements (Repeat, Condition and Condition Branch) follow an *orange *colour scheme. So the icons of these elements, the labels in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *view and the labels in the *Outline *view are orange.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Condition Branch
*Condition Branches *are the actual containers for the content of one *Condition*, i.e. the content to be displayed if a condition in one branch matches. The term *Branch *implies that a *Condition *– of course – may have multiple options, comparable to an *else if *statement. The last *Condition Branch *with no *expression *entered marks the *otherwise *branch.

### Add new condition branch
A new *Condition Branch *is inserted by right clicking an existing *Condition *– either in the *Designer *tab of the *Main view *or in the *Outline view *– and choosing *Add new Condition Branch *as shown in the figure below. You will then be prompted to enter the condition as XPath expression. If nothing is entered the condition branch becomes the *otherwise *branch. Please note that only one *otherwise *branch is possible.

In case more than one branch exists in the *Condition, *only one *active *branch is displayed in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *view. This symbolises that only one branch will be displayed in the actual PDF output. In order to switch between displayed branches it is possible to *Activate *branches using the context menu in the *Outline view*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 129. Elements &gt; Condition Branch*

Depending on their insertion level *Condition Branches *may contain *inline *or *block level *content.

### Fixed condition branches for preview
Clicking with the right mouse button on a *Condition Branch *in the *Outline*, there are the following options:

- Fix for preview

- Un-fix for preview

- Un-fix all for preview

The fixed *Condition Branches *are displayed in the preview (in PDF as well as ODT and RTF), but not in the *Design *view. In the *Design *view the individual branches can only be *activated*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 130. fixed condition branch*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Date Condition
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 131. Date Condition*

Using the Date Condition element, content can be enabled from a certain date onwards. This offers e.g. for advertising, which applies only after a defined date. Key to this is the date when the document is generated.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 132. Date Condition*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Date Branch
The start date for the underlying content is defined through the Date Branch element. If the option no condition is selected, an *otherwise *branch is created, i.e. specified content will be displayed until a start date is reached.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Language Switch
With the Language Switch element, content can be enabled for a certain language. This offers a solution for multilingual documents.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 133. Language Switch*

Under a Language Switch, various Language Branch elements with their languages can be positioned. In the Toolbar the currently selected language can be determined.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 134. Language selection*

A button ![](data:image/png;base64,) to hide unselected languages in the Outline view is in toolbar of the Outline view. This also hides the *Language Branch *element.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 135. Hide unselected languages*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Language Branch
The language for the underlying content is defined with the Language Branch element. The language is determined as soon as the Language Branch element is created. The language of a Language Branch element can also be changed later by double clicking on the Language Branch element in the Outline view.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 136. Define language*

When no language is selected or if it doesn’t exist in the specific branch, it selects the *otherwise *branch by default, i.e. specified content will be displayed when no other Language Branch fits for the currently selected language.

Note that languages can be defined with arbitrary granularity. While basic languages like en, de, fr, … will suffice for most applications, having different texts for en, en-US, en-GB is reasonably common. In this case, for the locales en-US and en-GB the respective texts will be used, and for plain en and all other en-based locales the text for en will be used. Although legitimate use cases may be rare, it is also possible to define a language branch for e.g. en- AU-Victoria-Melbourne. There is no limit on the number of levels, and values are not restricted to standard ISO language/country codes. Consider the maintainability of your templates before defining in-depth language branches, though.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAQAAAAPCAYAAADDNm69AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAWklEQVQImWP8OJlhAgMDgwEDBFxggXLsoQIMTAxogImBgeEDEv8BEwMDwwV0AQwtlAqwMDAwLGBgYDiA7FIBBgaGBKjABBYGBoYJDAinK2A1I4GBgaEAqrUBABADDKrrGXQyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Assertion
As the colour of the element indicates, the *Assertion *is a logical element as well. It provides the ability to wrap around any elements to perform defined assertions on an XPath expression during the transformation part of the rendering process. The failure outcome of the *Assertions *may vary depending on their settings. They may cause the process to abort the rendering, output a warning or ignore the result completely.

The easiest way to insert an *Assertion *is to right click an element in the *Outline *and choosing *Wrap with &gt; Assertion *to wrap the element and its children with an *Assertion*. The same procedure may be used to unwrap and remove the Assertion again. Additionally, it is possible to insert this element from the *Palette *or *Insert *menu.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 137. Wrap with Assertion*

An *Assertion *may assert one of the following seven types. They may assert that:

- *exists *– the provided XML node exists

- *true *– the XPath expression evaluates to logical true

- *count data *– the sum of XML nodes is minimal, maximal or equal to a specified value

- *string length *– the length of the XML nodes content is minimal, maximal or equal to a specified value

- *type check *– the type of the XML node is equal to a specified type (Types: boolean, date, decimal, string)

- *aggregate children *– all failed child *Assertion *did not exceed a specified level

- *count children *– the sum of successful child *Assertions *is minimal, maximal or equal to a specified value. It is additionally possible to specify how many child *Assertions *should be displayed.

Additionally, the *Assertion *has to specify one of these three levels, which will provide different results in case the *Assertion *fails:

- *error *– the rendering process aborts immediately

- *warning *– the rendering process proceeds, but the output will not contain the wrapped elements and a warning will be shown

- *ignore *– the result of the *Assertion *is ignored and the wrapped elements will not be shown in the output document

An optional message may be provided which will be displayed in the Events view if the

*Assertion *fails and a level of *warning *or *error *was specified.

There is also an option to negate the specified XPath expression, which will result in the exact opposite outcome. As an example, it is possible to assert if an XML node does not exists, if the negate options is set onto an *exists - Assertion*.

The following figure shows an example *Assertion*. It will evaluate if the XML node *“invoice/calldetails/…/calls” *is present at least once, otherwise the rendering process will abort with a message.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 138. Assertion example*

All assertions and their results are displayed in their own tab as an XML. To enable the tab, you have to enable the FO-tab in the preferences (see Chapter [FO](#_bookmark33))

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 139. Assertion tab*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Namespace
The *Namespaces *used for a template are displayed in the *Namespaces *node on top of the *Outline View*. ## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Decimal Format
The *Decimal Format *element is used to define decimal separators or group separators etc. Decimal Formats are created by either dragging a *Decimal Format *element from the Palette to the *Decimal Formats *node in the *Outline view*, or using the context menu on the same node. When using *Dynamic Value *elements, a *Decimal Format *can be assigned to format the output of the *Dynamic Value *by choosing type *number *and entering the name of the *Decimal Format *to use the *Format *input field. Values that can be applied to a *Decimal Format *are:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 146. Decimal Format properties*

**Attribute**

**Description**

*Name*

A unique name used to identify the *Decimal Format *within the template. If there is only one *Decimal Format *and the name is left blank it is considered as default and no name must be provided when referring to it.

*Decimal separator*

The symbol is used as decimal separator for numbers, e.g. to switch from dot to comma as decimal separator

*Group separator*

The symbol used for grouping numbers, e.g. dot for every *n *ciphers. The number of ciphers to add the separator after is defined via the *Pattern *of the *Dynamic Value*, e.g. ###.##0,00

*Infinity*

Some symbol to use instead of the default infinity sign (∞).

*Minus sign*

Some symbol to use instead of the default minus sign (-).

*Not-a-number-description*

Some symbol to use instead of NaN (*Not a Number*).

*Percent sign*

Some symbol to use instead of (%).

*Per-mille sign*

Some symbol to use instead of (‰).

*Zero digit*

Some symbol to use instead of (0).

*Pattern separator*

Some symbol to use instead of (;).

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Template Part
Being simple, reusable components *Template Parts *are possibly the most important concept in *Doxee Template Designer*.

*Template Parts *may contain single *inline *or *block level *elements up to complex structures and large parts of documents. This suggests a wide use for *Template Parts*. *Inline Template Parts *could be seasonal addressing for a customer, whereas *block level Template Parts *could for instance be an advertisement to be placed in a customer’s invoice chosen for the type of customer using a *Condition *(see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Condition](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#condition)). This particular example is a part of the *Infinica Mobile invoice *example, which can be found in the directory

*.\\Examples\INFINICA Mobile\Invoice\en*. The subsequent chapters and the *Doxee Template Designer *tutorial describes the use of *Template Parts*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 147. Elements &gt; Template Part*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Template Part Reference
Referring to a *Template Part *is simply performed by inserting a *Template Part Reference *element from the *Palette *and providing the *name*. Afterwards the reference to the declared *Template Part *is created. It is crucial to insert the reference on the content level the *Template Part *is designed for. That is, if the Template Part is *inline*, it is just possible to enter a reference to it on *inline *level, i.e. within a *block level *element. Therefore it is quite recommendable to insert the *Template Part References *in the *Outline *view. Having inserted the reference on the correct content level the content of the *Template Part *is displayed in the *Designer *tab of the *Main view*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 148. Elements &gt; Template Part Reference*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Template Part Parameter
A *Template Part Parameter *can be compared to a parameter in a program function and therefore can be used to pass data to the *Template Part*. From within the *Template Part *it can be called by *Dynamic Value *elements using $ plus the parameters name.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 149. Elements &gt; Template Part Parameter*

The correct use of a *Template Part Parameter *is shown above. Of course it is possible to apply multiple *Template Part Parameters *and as well to use them for *Template Parts *within *Template Part Packages*. Subsequently the use of a *Template Part Parameter *is described step by step:

- Create a new *Template Part *and name it

- Insert a *Template Part Parameter *(from the Palette) by dragging the element to the *Parameters *node of the *Template Part *in the *Outline view *and give it a name. If you enter a value to the *expression *field here, the value is used as the default value, if no explicit value is given in the reference.

- Insert a reference to the content of the *Template Part Parameter *via a *Dynamic Value *element using $&lt;name of the template part&gt;

- Create a *Template Part Reference *and rename it to the name given in step 1 – the *Problem View *will then show that a *Template Part Parameter *is missing.

- Insert a *Template Part Parameter *to the *Parameters *node of the reference

- Enter the parameters name in the input field

- The information, which is supposed to be passed to the *Template Part*, has to be entered in the *Expression *field.

- The content is then displayed in the output

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Insertion Point
An *Insertion Point *normally contains a number of available *Building Blocks *and defines by its own location on which document position in *Doxee Composer *they may be inserted by the user interactively.

An *Insertion Point *can be placed on block level as well as on inline level, which has to be in sync with the attribute *Miscellaenous &gt; inline &gt; true/false*. Additionally the following

attributes can be used to control the behaviour of the *Insertion Point*:

- *allow-repeats*: determines if the same *Building Block *[1: *Template Parts *which can be inserted by *Doxee Composer *users during runtime are also called *Building Blocks*.] may be inserted more than once

- *insertion-point-description*: may hold a brief description of the *Insertion Point*

- *insertion-point-id*: may hold a unique ID; If this is empty, *Doxee Composer *will generate its own during runtime. It is recommended to leave the *insertion-point-id *empty and allow *Doxee Composer *to generate its own unique ID. If you specify a static ID, and the *Insertion Point *is repeated (as part of a loop or a building block), the ID is no longer unique and the *Insertion Point *cannot be used properly in *Doxee Composer*.

- *insertion-point-name*: defines the name of the insertion point

- *max-count*: determines the total number of *Building Blocks *which may be inserted by the user (the allowed range of values is *0 *to *unbounded*)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 150. Insertion Point*

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Available Part / ![](data:image/png;base64,) Available Parts Group
These elements are used in *Insertion Points *to determine which *Template Parts *shall be available in the *Doxee Composer *document for insertion. Therefore one or more *Available Parts ![](data:image/png;base64,)* and/or one or more *Available Parts Groups ![](data:image/png;base64,)* can be inserted into the node *Available Parts ![](data:image/png;base64,)* of an *Insertion Point *element, either using the context menu or via drag and drop from the *Palette*, see ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Available Part](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#available-part-available-parts-group) / [![](data:image/png;base64,)](#_bookmark169) [Available Parts Group](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#available-part-available-parts-group).

An *Available Part *has to specify the name of an existing *Template Part *(which can be local or external) in the *Attribute XSL &gt; template-name*.

*Available Parts Group *elements have to specify a source which has to be an *Infinica *resource in which the desired *Template Parts *are contained. The *Insertion Point *will have all *Template Parts *which are included in the selected source available then.

*Insertion Points *also have to differ between inline and block level *Template Parts*. A block level *Insertion Point *can hold both types of *Template Parts*, while an *Insertion Point *on inline level can only hold inline *Template Parts*.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Chosen Part / ![](data:image/png;base64,) Chosen Part Group
It is possible to define a number of *Template Parts *which are already inserted in the *Insertion Point *when the document is opened in *Doxee Composer*. Therefor one more *Chosen Parts ![](data:image/png;base64,)* and/or one or more *Chosen Part Groups ![](data:image/png;base64,)* can be added to the *Chosen Part Group ![](data:image/png;base64,)* node either via the context menu or via drag and drop from the *Pallete*, see ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Available Part](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#available-part-available-parts-group) / [![](data:image/png;base64,)](#_bookmark169) [Available Parts Group](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#available-part-available-parts-group).

In case the *Insertion Point *is located on block level, *Chosen Parts *which are on inline level can be gathered in a *Chosen Part Group *which will summon the contained inline level *Template Parts *in a single paragraph. 

It is also possible to pass parameters to the *Chosen Parts*, which behave like regular *Template Part References*, as described in chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Template Part Parameter](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#template-part-parameter).

> Note

In order to be able to display the *Chosen Parts*, they also have to be inserted in the *Available Parts *node, either as *Available Part *or inside an *Available Parts Group*.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Refreshable Container
The Refreshable Container element was added in version 6.4. It wraps a section whose content can be refreshed by the user in *Doxee Composer*, in case either the template or the dynamic data have changed. For identification purposes during the refresh process, this element needs a unique name. So far, Refreshable Container elements are not supported within a *Repeat *or a *Template Part *element.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Composer Element
This element is used to control specific functionality in *Doxee Composer*, which is not (yet) supported in *Template Designer*. As of this release, there are the following known types of Composer elements:

### Composer Signature
The Composer signature element allows you to insert a signing area in the document. The signature area is marked as ***X ***in composer and defines the area to scribble your signature in a browser window using a mouse or a stylus pen. To achieve this, set the composer-element- type via *Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type *as *signature*. The rectangular dimensions (*layout *) of the signature area also have to be configured in *JSON syntax *via *Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-content*. For more information about *JSON syntax*, please refer to [*JSON specifications*](http://www.json.org/).

*Composer - Signature*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Composer Take-picture
This element offers you the capability to take live photos to be added to the document. The configuration is quite similar to the *composer signature *element except that you have to change the *composer-element-type *to *take-picture*.

*Composer - Take picture*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Composer gps-location
The Composer gps-location element allows you to insert into your document the current geographical position based on the GPS coordinates (latitude, longitude, altitude) of your device or a calculation of the web browser. The composer element type is configured via *Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type *as *gps-location-button*. You need as well to specify the attribute *composer-data *with any of these supported values: ***latitute, longitude, altitude or accuracy***. For more details, please refer to composer documentation.

*Composer - Gps location (latitude,longitude &amp; altitude)*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Composer Barcode-scanner
The Composer barcode element allows you to scan and recognize various barcode symbologies from your document. The recognizer reads the barcodes via built-in camera on your device. The barcode picture is captured and the decoded barcode information is saved on your document. The attribute *Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type *gets the value *barcode*.

*Composer - Barcode recognition*

*![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*

### Composer Autocomplete
This composer form element will show a predefined result set in Composer, coming from an outer webservice as you type. You are able to select any pop-downed recommendation, or just type more to get other more exact recommendations. But you do not have to select any of these, if do not want. The attribute *Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type *must be set to *autocomplete *and the attribute *composer-element-content *must contain a JSON including an external process. An example JSON is: {"process": "composer-autocomplete.ipd", "filter": {"yourfilter1": "value1", "yourfilter2": "value2" }} In this example an external process (Doxee Process Engine) is called and the relults will be filtered as set. You can also set the attributes *width*, *formfield-field-name *and *formfield-target*.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Apply Templates
Representing the XSLT element *Apply Templates*, this is an advanced element for experienced users. Depending on an XML it is possible to call templates, e.g. *Infinica Template Parts*. Using *Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; src *the path within the data structure assigned to the *Infinica *template, to the set of XSL templates to use, is specified (See chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Data Inputs](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-views-1#data-inputs).

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Infinica Template
This element allows adding other *Infinica Template *resources to the current template. All *Infinica Templates *with the file extension *ITX *are appropriate for that. This way different kinds of packages can be added to a template, e.g. template parts and style packages in a single file.

This element is applicable on the *External Resources *node, either by drag and drop from the *Palette *or by using the context menu item *Add new… &gt; Infincia Template*.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) XSL Include
*XSL include *represents the XSL element *Include *and allows including an external XML file. An *XSL include *element is entered to the *External Resources *node in the *Outline View *(see chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAkAAAAJCAYAAADgkQYQAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAcklEQVQYlXXNQRGDMBSE4T/QOxw5RgISNk6KgzpCAw7ioJUQCaDg9ZIyKSR7ejvzzVtHjqQVeFJJ/ztSSpv33gPzFXWX/gL2JpI0ABEYq6gA5dT5sW+AT+4TMD8aQDHGA1gk4cyMEIJVwH/MDEnvPH3LF5cKIzX9/jIyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) [External Resources](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-document-structure#external-resources)) Using *Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; src_ *the source can be specified.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Insertion Point States
This element allows the generation of *Insertion Point *states for the *Doxee Composer*. See the *Doxee Composer User Guide *for more information.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Output Configurations
This element allows to control which components of the current *Infinica Template *will be included when the XSL is generated, which is also performed when *Infinica Templates *are added as external resources. When a new template is created, you are asked which type of template you intend to create, see chapter [New Template](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-actions-1#new-template). Thereupon a corresponding output configuration for the selected type will be set. If you selected the option decide later or in case you want to perform further configurations, the *Output Configuration *element

which is found in the *Outline View *can be edited by double clicking it.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 151. Output Configuration*

You can either select a preconfigured output configuration (e.g. *Template Part Package *or *Style Package*) or define yourself which template components shall be exported just by checking and unchecking the single elements. So you could create a package which can be used to hold *Style Packages *and *Decimal Formats *for other templates that use it.

The FO target path is used when the XSL generation is triggered via a call from the command line to specify where the FO and IDX files are supposed to be saved.

> Important

Not every combination of output component can be used to produce a valid document! The template or one of the referenced templates has to export the *Page Sequences *element but be able to render the document.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAPCAYAAADtc08vAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAbUlEQVQokbWTXQ7AIAiDcdnB6Ml7NPdEgr/gsn1vRqitYlHVSrKIiACoksDX35PNbTOAZn2dFM8YBKwJQOhmKmBNJN856MW8o2MBH2MVJ3QQ8f0r9A5+v4NhEvuTohiNgM34CdsIGYqqpn7gige2ojEoHb/5PgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==)  Schemas
This element is used by *Template Designer *to collect all schemas which are referenced in a data input (see ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Data Inputs](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-views-1#data-inputs)).
